item.title: Senecio linearifolius var. denticulatus
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Lots of young plants coming up close to the Baw Baw Alpine Village. S. linearifolius var. latifolius also grows nearby and it is probably one month ahead of var. denticulatus re flowering time.

item.title: Thelymitra cyanea
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Growing in boggy area with plants like Drosera arcturi. From Neville Walsh, they are "very prone to that inky tip damage, although they seem to flower OK from that. It's pretty much an obligate dweller of sphagnum peats."

item.title: Olearia phlogopappa subsp. continentalis
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Shrubs to about 2.5m tall. At Mushroom Rocks.

item.dc:creator: russell

item.title: Caladenia alpina
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Despite considerable variation I think all 5 plants pictured are Caladenia alpina. Last 2 pics are of the same plant.

item.title: Montia fontana
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Only subsp. fontana has been recorded at Mt Baw Baw but I can't confirm without seed.

item.title: Leptostigma breviflorum
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: A ground-hugging, dense, soft mat spreading to 50cm+. ID by Neville Walsh. A long way out of range for this species.

item.title: Psychrophila introloba
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Growing in a marshy area with Drosera arcturi. ID by Neville Walsh.

item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Single plant growing in a rock face near Walhalla. ID by Neville Walsh.

item.title: Lycopodium fastigiatum
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Thousands of plants but only two seen in flower.

item.title: Schoenus calyptratus
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Tiny plants spreading to form a mat in inundated areas.

item.title: Ozothamnus secundiflorus
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Leaves with midrib on lower surface tomentose = O. secundiflorus. Glabrous midrib = O. thyrsoideus.

item.title: Correa lawrenceana var. latrobeana
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: All plants had finished flowering except this one which was mostly in bud.

item.title: Richea victoriana
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: 1st pic shows glabrous flowering stem. No gap between leaves and first flower is another feature compared to R. continentis which has 4cm+ gap between leaves and flowers and a pubescent flowering stem

item.title: Richea continentis
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: 3rd pic shows pubescent flowering stem. 4cm+ gap between leaves and first flower is another feature compared to R. victoriana which has no gap between leaves and flowers and a glabrous flowering stem.

item.title: Viola hederacea subsp. nov. (Baw Baws)
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Key features are 1) Flowers barely exceed leaves and 2) Flowers nod down when open (pic 1, 2 & 3) or don't open much at all (pic 4 & 5). Only 2 of about 100 flowers were open on this 20 degree, sunny-showery day.

item.title: Viola eminens

item.description: Short stem and leaves not perfect for eminens. Other plants were a little taller. Apparently Baw Baw is renowned for unusual Viola.
